NBA 2020 Season Statistics Analysis

By: Andy Babay and Melvin Molina

Introduction

For our project we decided to analyze the NBA 2020 season. Although it was a very "different" season to say the very least considering the ongoing Covid-19 pandemic we are facing. The statistics attracted us enough to focus our project on it. We will be going into the details regarding pay, age, and positional statistics. With the usage of many libraries including, but not exclusive to pandas, sklearn, and numpy. This project will solely analyze the 2020 NBA season. Meaning, the data we will be gathering and conducting our analysis on will solely by on this past season. As a needed reminder, the Los Angeles Lakers are the current NBA Champions. Lastly, before we begin our data analysis, rest in paradise Kobe Bryant.

Retreiving Data

To begin our data analysis it is important to source our information from somewhere legitament. For our project we will be using https://www.basketball-reference.com. This site is known for having a mecca of NBA statistics so it's the perfect spot for us to start

Organizing Data

Once we have read in our data via BeautifulSoup, we begin to add the data into our overall dataframe in order to further analyze our information better. We place the data into seperate arrays, which will allow us to then converge the arrays with ease, due to the synchronous processing.

Data Gathering for Salaries

Although we have organized our NBA '20 season statistics, we are also interested in analyzing players salaries. Although our original source has a variety of player statistics, it does not have player salaries. For this information, we head to ESPN. On the site on ESPN we find specific player salary information. We will be using beautifulsoup to parse this information. We start by creating a new array solely for the salaries. Then we can move the information elsewhere.

In [58]:
salary = []
PAGE_LEN=14

for i in range(1,PAGE_LEN+1):
    url = "http://www.espn.com/nba/salaries/_/year/2020/page/" + str(i)
    data = requests.get(url)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(data.content, "lxml")
    temp = soup.find_all("tr", {"class": "oddrow"})
    for i in temp:
        table_1= i.text
        salary.append(table_1)   
    temp2 = soup.find_all("tr", {"class": "evenrow"})
    for i in temp2:
        table_2 = i.text
        salary.append(table_2)

Cleaning data

Although we've retreived the salary information from ESPN, it's clear the parsing of the data directly is not transfering well. With the data transfering as a mix between player name and salary. We then use Regex to be able to seperate the player name and the player salary while placing the results into an array we will use later on. Seperating the name and salary correctly. Tidying the data appropriately.

In [59]:
regex = "\$.+"
regex2 = "[a-zA-z]+\s*[a-zA-z]*"

#now its time to clean the data
players = []
p_salary = []

for i in range(0,len(salary)):
    
    x = re.search(regex2,salary[i].split(',')[0])[0]
    y = re.search(regex,salary[i])[0].split('$')[1].replace(',','')
    
    players.append(x)
    p_salary.append(float(y))

Turnovers

Although it's good to analyze the good statistics such as three point attempts and field goals made. We also must turn to the negative statistics as well. One example is turnovers. If you're not familiar with turnovers, it's when a player looses posession. Also another impacting statistic is the Personal Foul count. Now we can try to see if there's a correlation between the two. For example, in a game if a player is consistently turning the ball over. Is that player going to be more aggresive and become more succeptible to a personal foul than a player with less turnovers? Our graph provides us with an answer to that. With the usage of linear regression we can see that the higher the amount of turnovers a player has, the higher amount of personal fouls that player will commit in that game. This is not concrete evidence, as time played could also play a big role in the amount of personal fouls. But we have a good amount of evidence to claim that turnovers may be influential in players getting more personal fouls based on a higher count of turnovers.
